9183 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//
9184 // Type Compatibility Testing
9185 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//
9186 
9187 /// areCompatVectorTypes - Return true if the two specified vector types are
9188 /// compatible.
9189 static bool areCompatVectorTypes(const VectorType *LHS,
9190  const VectorType *RHS) {
9191  assert(LHS->isCanonicalUnqualified() && RHS->isCanonicalUnqualified());
9192  return LHS->getElementType() == RHS->getElementType() &&
9193  LHS->getNumElements() == RHS->getNumElements();
9194 }
9195 
9196 /// areCompatMatrixTypes - Return true if the two specified matrix types are
9197 /// compatible.
9198 static bool areCompatMatrixTypes(const ConstantMatrixType *LHS,
9199  const ConstantMatrixType *RHS) {
9200  assert(LHS->isCanonicalUnqualified() && RHS->isCanonicalUnqualified());
9201  return LHS->getElementType() == RHS->getElementType() &&
9202  LHS->getNumRows() == RHS->getNumRows() &&
9203  LHS->getNumColumns() == RHS->getNumColumns();
9204 }
9205 
9206 bool ASTContext::areCompatibleVectorTypes(QualType FirstVec,
9207  QualType SecondVec) {
9208  assert(FirstVec->isVectorType() && "FirstVec should be a vector type");
9209  assert(SecondVec->isVectorType() && "SecondVec should be a vector type");
9210 
9211  if (hasSameUnqualifiedType(FirstVec, SecondVec))
9212  return true;
9213 
9214  // Treat Neon vector types and most AltiVec vector types as if they are the
9215  // equivalent GCC vector types.
9216  const auto *First = FirstVec->castAs<VectorType>();
9217  const auto *Second = SecondVec->castAs<VectorType>();
9218  if (First->getNumElements() == Second->getNumElements() &&
9219  hasSameType(First->getElementType(), Second->getElementType()) &&
9220  First->getVectorKind() != VectorType::AltiVecPixel &&
9221  First->getVectorKind() != VectorType::AltiVecBool &&
9222  Second->getVectorKind() != VectorType::AltiVecPixel &&
9223  Second->getVectorKind() != VectorType::AltiVecBool &&
9224  First->getVectorKind() != VectorType::SveFixedLengthDataVector &&
9225  First->getVectorKind() != VectorType::SveFixedLengthPredicateVector &&
9226  Second->getVectorKind() != VectorType::SveFixedLengthDataVector &&
9227  Second->getVectorKind() != VectorType::SveFixedLengthPredicateVector)
9228  return true;
9229 
9230  return false;
9231 }
9232 
9233 /// getSVETypeSize - Return SVE vector or predicate register size.
9234 static uint64_t getSVETypeSize(ASTContext &Context, const BuiltinType *Ty) {
9235  assert(Ty->isVLSTBuiltinType() && "Invalid SVE Type");
9236  return Ty->getKind() == BuiltinType::SveBool
9237  ? (Context.getLangOpts().VScaleMin * 128) / Context.getCharWidth()
9238  : Context.getLangOpts().VScaleMin * 128;
9239 }
9240 
9241 bool ASTContext::areCompatibleSveTypes(QualType FirstType,
9242  QualType SecondType) {
9243  assert(((FirstType->isSizelessBuiltinType() && SecondType->isVectorType()) ||
9244  (FirstType->isVectorType() && SecondType->isSizelessBuiltinType())) &&
9245  "Expected SVE builtin type and vector type!");
9246 
9247  auto IsValidCast = [this](QualType FirstType, QualType SecondType) {
9248  if (const auto *BT = FirstType->getAs<BuiltinType>()) {
9249  if (const auto *VT = SecondType->getAs<VectorType>()) {
9250  // Predicates have the same representation as uint8 so we also have to
9251  // check the kind to make these types incompatible.
9252  if (VT->getVectorKind() == VectorType::SveFixedLengthPredicateVector)
9253  return BT->getKind() == BuiltinType::SveBool;
9254  else if (VT->getVectorKind() == VectorType::SveFixedLengthDataVector)
9255  return VT->getElementType().getCanonicalType() ==
9256  FirstType->getSveEltType(*this);
9257  else if (VT->getVectorKind() == VectorType::GenericVector)
9258  return getTypeSize(SecondType) == getSVETypeSize(*this, BT) &&
9259  hasSameType(VT->getElementType(),
9260  getBuiltinVectorTypeInfo(BT).ElementType);
9261  }
9262  }
9263  return false;
9264  };
9265 
9266  return IsValidCast(FirstType, SecondType) ||
9267  IsValidCast(SecondType, FirstType);
9268 }
9269 
9270 bool ASTContext::areLaxCompatibleSveTypes(QualType FirstType,
9271  QualType SecondType) {
9272  assert(((FirstType->isSizelessBuiltinType() && SecondType->isVectorType()) ||
9273  (FirstType->isVectorType() && SecondType->isSizelessBuiltinType())) &&
9274  "Expected SVE builtin type and vector type!");
9275 
9276  auto IsLaxCompatible = [this](QualType FirstType, QualType SecondType) {
9277  const auto *BT = FirstType->getAs<BuiltinType>();
9278  if (!BT)
9279  return false;
9280 
9281  const auto *VecTy = SecondType->getAs<VectorType>();
9282  if (VecTy &&
9283  (VecTy->getVectorKind() == VectorType::SveFixedLengthDataVector ||
9284  VecTy->getVectorKind() == VectorType::GenericVector)) {
9285  const LangOptions::LaxVectorConversionKind LVCKind =
9286  getLangOpts().getLaxVectorConversions();
9287 
9288  // Can not convert between sve predicates and sve vectors because of
9289  // different size.
9290  if (BT->getKind() == BuiltinType::SveBool &&
9291  VecTy->getVectorKind() == VectorType::SveFixedLengthDataVector)
9292  return false;
9293 
9294  // If __ARM_FEATURE_SVE_BITS != N do not allow GNU vector lax conversion.
9295  // "Whenever __ARM_FEATURE_SVE_BITS==N, GNUT implicitly
9296  // converts to VLAT and VLAT implicitly converts to GNUT."
9297  // ACLE Spec Version 00bet6, 3.7.3.2. Behavior common to vectors and
9298  // predicates.
9299  if (VecTy->getVectorKind() == VectorType::GenericVector &&
9300  getTypeSize(SecondType) != getSVETypeSize(*this, BT))
9301  return false;
9302 
9303  // If -flax-vector-conversions=all is specified, the types are
9304  // certainly compatible.
9305  if (LVCKind == LangOptions::LaxVectorConversionKind::All)
9306  return true;
9307 
9308  // If -flax-vector-conversions=integer is specified, the types are
9309  // compatible if the elements are integer types.
9310  if (LVCKind == LangOptions::LaxVectorConversionKind::Integer)
9311  return VecTy->getElementType().getCanonicalType()->isIntegerType() &&
9312  FirstType->getSveEltType(*this)->isIntegerType();
9313  }
9314 
9315  return false;
9316  };
9317 
9318  return IsLaxCompatible(FirstType, SecondType) ||
9319  IsLaxCompatible(SecondType, FirstType);
9320 }
9321 
9322 bool ASTContext::hasDirectOwnershipQualifier(QualType Ty) const {
9323  while (true) {
9324  // __strong id
9325  if (const AttributedType *Attr = dyn_cast<AttributedType>(Ty)) {
9326  if (Attr->getAttrKind() == attr::ObjCOwnership)
9327  return true;
9328 
9329  Ty = Attr->getModifiedType();
9330 
9331  // X *__strong (...)
9332  } else if (const ParenType *Paren = dyn_cast<ParenType>(Ty)) {
9333  Ty = Paren->getInnerType();
9334 
9335  // We do not want to look through typedefs, typeof(expr),
9336  // typeof(type), or any other way that the type is somehow
9337  // abstracted.
9338  } else {
9339  return false;
9340  }
9341  }
9342 }
9343 
9344 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//
9345 // ObjCQualifiedIdTypesAreCompatible - Compatibility testing for qualified id's.
9346 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//
9347 
9348 /// ProtocolCompatibleWithProtocol - return 'true' if 'lProto' is in the
9349 /// inheritance hierarchy of 'rProto'.
9350 bool
9351 ASTContext::ProtocolCompatibleWithProtocol(ObjCProtocolDecl *lProto,
9352  ObjCProtocolDecl *rProto) const {
9353  if (declaresSameEntity(lProto, rProto))
9354  return true;
9355  for (auto *PI : rProto->protocols())
9356  if (ProtocolCompatibleWithProtocol(lProto, PI))
9357  return true;
9358  return false;
9359 }
9360 
9361 /// ObjCQualifiedClassTypesAreCompatible - compare Class<pr,...> and
9362 /// Class<pr1, ...>.
9363 bool ASTContext::ObjCQualifiedClassTypesAreCompatible(
9364  const ObjCObjectPointerType *lhs, const ObjCObjectPointerType *rhs) {
9365  for (auto *lhsProto : lhs->quals()) {
9366  bool match = false;
9367  for (auto *rhsProto : rhs->quals()) {
9368  if (ProtocolCompatibleWithProtocol(lhsProto, rhsProto)) {
9369  match = true;
9370  break;
9371  }
9372  }
9373  if (!match)
9374  return false;
9375  }
9376  return true;
9377 }
9378 
9379 /// ObjCQualifiedIdTypesAreCompatible - We know that one of lhs/rhs is an
9380 /// ObjCQualifiedIDType.
9381 bool ASTContext::ObjCQualifiedIdTypesAreCompatible(
9382  const ObjCObjectPointerType *lhs, const ObjCObjectPointerType *rhs,
9383  bool compare) {
9384  // Allow id<P..> and an 'id' in all cases.
9385  if (lhs->isObjCIdType() || rhs->isObjCIdType())
9386  return true;
9387 
9388  // Don't allow id<P..> to convert to Class or Class<P..> in either direction.
9389  if (lhs->isObjCClassType() || lhs->isObjCQualifiedClassType() ||
9390  rhs->isObjCClassType() || rhs->isObjCQualifiedClassType())
9391  return false;
9392 
9393  if (lhs->isObjCQualifiedIdType()) {
9394  if (rhs->qual_empty()) {
9395  // If the RHS is a unqualified interface pointer "NSString*",
9396  // make sure we check the class hierarchy.
9397  if (ObjCInterfaceDecl *rhsID = rhs->getInterfaceDecl()) {
9398  for (auto *I : lhs->quals()) {
9399  // when comparing an id<P> on lhs with a static type on rhs,
9400  // see if static class implements all of id's protocols, directly or
9401  // through its super class and categories.
9402  if (!rhsID->ClassImplementsProtocol(I, true))
9403  return false;
9404  }
9405  }
9406  // If there are no qualifiers and no interface, we have an 'id'.
9407  return true;
9408  }
9409  // Both the right and left sides have qualifiers.
9410  for (auto *lhsProto : lhs->quals()) {
9411  bool match = false;
9412 
9413  // when comparing an id<P> on lhs with a static type on rhs,
9414  // see if static class implements all of id's protocols, directly or
9415  // through its super class and categories.
9416  for (auto *rhsProto : rhs->quals()) {
9417  if (ProtocolCompatibleWithProtocol(lhsProto, rhsProto) ||
9418  (compare && ProtocolCompatibleWithProtocol(rhsProto, lhsProto))) {
9419  match = true;
9420  break;
9421  }
9422  }
9423  // If the RHS is a qualified interface pointer "NSString<P>*",
9424  // make sure we check the class hierarchy.
9425  if (ObjCInterfaceDecl *rhsID = rhs->getInterfaceDecl()) {
9426  for (auto *I : lhs->quals()) {
9427  // when comparing an id<P> on lhs with a static type on rhs,
9428  // see if static class implements all of id's protocols, directly or
9429  // through its super class and categories.
9430  if (rhsID->ClassImplementsProtocol(I, true)) {
9431  match = true;
9432  break;
9433  }
9434  }
9435  }
9436  if (!match)
9437  return false;
9438  }
9439 
9440  return true;
9441  }
9442 
9443  assert(rhs->isObjCQualifiedIdType() && "One of the LHS/RHS should be id<x>");
9444 
9445  if (lhs->getInterfaceType()) {
9446  // If both the right and left sides have qualifiers.
9447  for (auto *lhsProto : lhs->quals()) {
9448  bool match = false;
9449 
9450  // when comparing an id<P> on rhs with a static type on lhs,
9451  // see if static class implements all of id's protocols, directly or
9452  // through its super class and categories.
9453  // First, lhs protocols in the qualifier list must be found, direct
9454  // or indirect in rhs's qualifier list or it is a mismatch.
9455  for (auto *rhsProto : rhs->quals()) {
9456  if (ProtocolCompatibleWithProtocol(lhsProto, rhsProto) ||
9457  (compare && ProtocolCompatibleWithProtocol(rhsProto, lhsProto))) {
9458  match = true;
9459  break;
9460  }
9461  }
9462  if (!match)
9463  return false;
9464  }
9465 
9466  // Static class's protocols, or its super class or category protocols
9467  // must be found, direct or indirect in rhs's qualifier list or it is a mismatch.
9468  if (ObjCInterfaceDecl *lhsID = lhs->getInterfaceDecl()) {
9469  llvm::SmallPtrSet<ObjCProtocolDecl *, 8> LHSInheritedProtocols;
9470  CollectInheritedProtocols(lhsID, LHSInheritedProtocols);
9471  // This is rather dubious but matches gcc's behavior. If lhs has
9472  // no type qualifier and its class has no static protocol(s)
9473  // assume that it is mismatch.
9474  if (LHSInheritedProtocols.empty() && lhs->qual_empty())
9475  return false;
9476  for (auto *lhsProto : LHSInheritedProtocols) {
9477  bool match = false;
9478  for (auto *rhsProto : rhs->quals()) {
9479  if (ProtocolCompatibleWithProtocol(lhsProto, rhsProto) ||
9480  (compare && ProtocolCompatibleWithProtocol(rhsProto, lhsProto))) {
9481  match = true;
9482  break;
9483  }
9484  }
9485  if (!match)
9486  return false;
9487  }
9488  }
9489  return true;
9490  }
9491  return false;
9492 }
9493 
9494 /// canAssignObjCInterfaces - Return true if the two interface types are
9495 /// compatible for assignment from RHS to LHS. This handles validation of any
9496 /// protocol qualifiers on the LHS or RHS.
9497 bool ASTContext::canAssignObjCInterfaces(const ObjCObjectPointerType *LHSOPT,
9498  const ObjCObjectPointerType *RHSOPT) {
9499  const ObjCObjectType* LHS = LHSOPT->getObjectType();
9500  const ObjCObjectType* RHS = RHSOPT->getObjectType();
9501 
9502  // If either type represents the built-in 'id' type, return true.
9503  if (LHS->isObjCUnqualifiedId() || RHS->isObjCUnqualifiedId())
9504  return true;
9505 
9506  // Function object that propagates a successful result or handles
9507  // __kindof types.
9508  auto finish = [&](bool succeeded) -> bool {
9509  if (succeeded)
9510  return true;
9511 
9512  if (!RHS->isKindOfType())
9513  return false;
9514 
9515  // Strip off __kindof and protocol qualifiers, then check whether
9516  // we can assign the other way.
9517  return canAssignObjCInterfaces(RHSOPT->stripObjCKindOfTypeAndQuals(*this),
9518  LHSOPT->stripObjCKindOfTypeAndQuals(*this));
9519  };
9520 
9521  // Casts from or to id<P> are allowed when the other side has compatible
9522  // protocols.
9523  if (LHS->isObjCQualifiedId() || RHS->isObjCQualifiedId()) {
9524  return finish(ObjCQualifiedIdTypesAreCompatible(LHSOPT, RHSOPT, false));
9525  }
9526 
9527  // Verify protocol compatibility for casts from Class<P1> to Class<P2>.
9528  if (LHS->isObjCQualifiedClass() && RHS->isObjCQualifiedClass()) {
9529  return finish(ObjCQualifiedClassTypesAreCompatible(LHSOPT, RHSOPT));
9530  }
9531 
9532  // Casts from Class to Class<Foo>, or vice-versa, are allowed.
9533  if (LHS->isObjCClass() && RHS->isObjCClass()) {
9534  return true;
9535  }
9536 
9537  // If we have 2 user-defined types, fall into that path.
9538  if (LHS->getInterface() && RHS->getInterface()) {
9539  return finish(canAssignObjCInterfaces(LHS, RHS));
9540  }
9541 
9542  return false;
9543 }
9544 
9545 /// canAssignObjCInterfacesInBlockPointer - This routine is specifically written
9546 /// for providing type-safety for objective-c pointers used to pass/return
9547 /// arguments in block literals. When passed as arguments, passing 'A*' where
9548 /// 'id' is expected is not OK. Passing 'Sub *" where 'Super *" is expected is
9549 /// not OK. For the return type, the opposite is not OK.
9550 bool ASTContext::canAssignObjCInterfacesInBlockPointer(
9551  const ObjCObjectPointerType *LHSOPT,
9552  const ObjCObjectPointerType *RHSOPT,
9553  bool BlockReturnType) {
9554 
9555  // Function object that propagates a successful result or handles
9556  // __kindof types.
9557  auto finish = [&](bool succeeded) -> bool {
9558  if (succeeded)
9559  return true;
9560 
9561  const ObjCObjectPointerType *Expected = BlockReturnType ? RHSOPT : LHSOPT;
9562  if (!Expected->isKindOfType())
9563  return false;
9564 
9565  // Strip off __kindof and protocol qualifiers, then check whether
9566  // we can assign the other way.
9567  return canAssignObjCInterfacesInBlockPointer(
9568  RHSOPT->stripObjCKindOfTypeAndQuals(*this),
9569  LHSOPT->stripObjCKindOfTypeAndQuals(*this),
9570  BlockReturnType);
9571  };
9572 
9573  if (RHSOPT->isObjCBuiltinType() || LHSOPT->isObjCIdType())
9574  return true;
9575 
9576  if (LHSOPT->isObjCBuiltinType()) {
9577  return finish(RHSOPT->isObjCBuiltinType() ||
9578  RHSOPT->isObjCQualifiedIdType());
9579  }
9580 
9581  if (LHSOPT->isObjCQualifiedIdType() || RHSOPT->isObjCQualifiedIdType()) {
9582  if (getLangOpts().CompatibilityQualifiedIdBlockParamTypeChecking)
9583  // Use for block parameters previous type checking for compatibility.
9584  return finish(ObjCQualifiedIdTypesAreCompatible(LHSOPT, RHSOPT, false) ||
9585  // Or corrected type checking as in non-compat mode.
9586  (!BlockReturnType &&
9587  ObjCQualifiedIdTypesAreCompatible(RHSOPT, LHSOPT, false)));
9588  else
9589  return finish(ObjCQualifiedIdTypesAreCompatible(
9590  (BlockReturnType ? LHSOPT : RHSOPT),
9591  (BlockReturnType ? RHSOPT : LHSOPT), false));
9592  }
9593 
9594  const ObjCInterfaceType* LHS = LHSOPT->getInterfaceType();
9595  const ObjCInterfaceType* RHS = RHSOPT->getInterfaceType();
9596  if (LHS && RHS) { // We have 2 user-defined types.
9597  if (LHS != RHS) {
9598  if (LHS->getDecl()->isSuperClassOf(RHS->getDecl()))
9599  return finish(BlockReturnType);
9600  if (RHS->getDecl()->isSuperClassOf(LHS->getDecl()))
9601  return finish(!BlockReturnType);
9602  }
9603  else
9604  return true;
9605  }
9606  return false;
9607 }
9608 
9609 /// Comparison routine for Objective-C protocols to be used with
9610 /// llvm::array_pod_sort.
9611 static int compareObjCProtocolsByName(ObjCProtocolDecl * const *lhs,
9612  ObjCProtocolDecl * const *rhs) {
9613  return (*lhs)->getName().compare((*rhs)->getName());
9614 }
9615 
9616 /// getIntersectionOfProtocols - This routine finds the intersection of set
9617 /// of protocols inherited from two distinct objective-c pointer objects with
9618 /// the given common base.
9619 /// It is used to build composite qualifier list of the composite type of
9620 /// the conditional expression involving two objective-c pointer objects.
9621 static
9622 void getIntersectionOfProtocols(ASTContext &Context,
9623  const ObjCInterfaceDecl *CommonBase,
9624  const ObjCObjectPointerType *LHSOPT,
9625  const ObjCObjectPointerType *RHSOPT,
9626  SmallVectorImpl<ObjCProtocolDecl *> &IntersectionSet) {
9627 
9628  const ObjCObjectType* LHS = LHSOPT->getObjectType();
9629  const ObjCObjectType* RHS = RHSOPT->getObjectType();
9630  assert(LHS->getInterface() && "LHS must have an interface base");
9631  assert(RHS->getInterface() && "RHS must have an interface base");
9632 
9633  // Add all of the protocols for the LHS.
9634  llvm::SmallPtrSet<ObjCProtocolDecl *, 8> LHSProtocolSet;
9635 
9636  // Start with the protocol qualifiers.
9637  for (auto proto : LHS->quals()) {
9638  Context.CollectInheritedProtocols(proto, LHSProtocolSet);
9639  }
9640 
9641  // Also add the protocols associated with the LHS interface.
9642  Context.CollectInheritedProtocols(LHS->getInterface(), LHSProtocolSet);
9643 
9644  // Add all of the protocols for the RHS.
9645  llvm::SmallPtrSet<ObjCProtocolDecl *, 8> RHSProtocolSet;
9646 
9647  // Start with the protocol qualifiers.
9648  for (auto proto : RHS->quals()) {
9649  Context.CollectInheritedProtocols(proto, RHSProtocolSet);
9650  }
9651 
9652  // Also add the protocols associated with the RHS interface.
9653  Context.CollectInheritedProtocols(RHS->getInterface(), RHSProtocolSet);
9654 
9655  // Compute the intersection of the collected protocol sets.
9656  for (auto proto : LHSProtocolSet) {
9657  if (RHSProtocolSet.count(proto))
9658  IntersectionSet.push_back(proto);
9659  }
9660 
9661  // Compute the set of protocols that is implied by either the common type or
9662  // the protocols within the intersection.
9663  llvm::SmallPtrSet<ObjCProtocolDecl *, 8> ImpliedProtocols;
9664  Context.CollectInheritedProtocols(CommonBase, ImpliedProtocols);
9665 
9666  // Remove any implied protocols from the list of inherited protocols.
9667  if (!ImpliedProtocols.empty()) {
9668  llvm::erase_if(IntersectionSet, [&](ObjCProtocolDecl *proto) -> bool {
9669  return ImpliedProtocols.contains(proto);
9670  });
9671  }
9672 
9673  // Sort the remaining protocols by name.
9674  llvm::array_pod_sort(IntersectionSet.begin(), IntersectionSet.end(),
9675  compareObjCProtocolsByName);
9676 }
9677 
9678 /// Determine whether the first type is a subtype of the second.
9679 static bool canAssignObjCObjectTypes(ASTContext &ctx, QualType lhs,
9680  QualType rhs) {
9681  // Common case: two object pointers.
9682  const auto *lhsOPT = lhs->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
9683  const auto *rhsOPT = rhs->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
9684  if (lhsOPT && rhsOPT)
9685  return ctx.canAssignObjCInterfaces(lhsOPT, rhsOPT);
9686 
9687  // Two block pointers.
9688  const auto *lhsBlock = lhs->getAs<BlockPointerType>();
9689  const auto *rhsBlock = rhs->getAs<BlockPointerType>();
9690  if (lhsBlock && rhsBlock)
9691  return ctx.typesAreBlockPointerCompatible(lhs, rhs);
9692 
9693  // If either is an unqualified 'id' and the other is a block, it's
9694  // acceptable.
9695  if ((lhsOPT && lhsOPT->isObjCIdType() && rhsBlock) ||
9696  (rhsOPT && rhsOPT->isObjCIdType() && lhsBlock))
9697  return true;
9698 
9699  return false;
9700 }
9701 
9702 // Check that the given Objective-C type argument lists are equivalent.
9703 static bool sameObjCTypeArgs(ASTContext &ctx,
9704  const ObjCInterfaceDecl *iface,
9705  ArrayRef<QualType> lhsArgs,
9706  ArrayRef<QualType> rhsArgs,
9707  bool stripKindOf) {
9708  if (lhsArgs.size() != rhsArgs.size())
9709  return false;
9710 
9711  ObjCTypeParamList *typeParams = iface->getTypeParamList();
9712  for (unsigned i = 0, n = lhsArgs.size(); i != n; ++i) {
9713  if (ctx.hasSameType(lhsArgs[i], rhsArgs[i]))
9714  continue;
9715 
9716  switch (typeParams->begin()[i]->getVariance()) {
9717  case ObjCTypeParamVariance::Invariant:
9718  if (!stripKindOf ||
9719  !ctx.hasSameType(lhsArgs[i].stripObjCKindOfType(ctx),
9720  rhsArgs[i].stripObjCKindOfType(ctx))) {
9721  return false;
9722  }
9723  break;
9724 
9725  case ObjCTypeParamVariance::Covariant:
9726  if (!canAssignObjCObjectTypes(ctx, lhsArgs[i], rhsArgs[i]))
9727  return false;
9728  break;
9729 
9730  case ObjCTypeParamVariance::Contravariant:
9731  if (!canAssignObjCObjectTypes(ctx, rhsArgs[i], lhsArgs[i]))
9732  return false;
9733  break;
9734  }
9735  }
9736 
9737  return true;
9738 }
9739 
9740 QualType ASTContext::areCommonBaseCompatible(
9741  const ObjCObjectPointerType *Lptr,
9742  const ObjCObjectPointerType *Rptr) {
9743  const ObjCObjectType *LHS = Lptr->getObjectType();
9744  const ObjCObjectType *RHS = Rptr->getObjectType();
9745  const ObjCInterfaceDecl* LDecl = LHS->getInterface();
9746  const ObjCInterfaceDecl* RDecl = RHS->getInterface();
9747 
9748  if (!LDecl || !RDecl)
9749  return {};
9750 
9751  // When either LHS or RHS is a kindof type, we should return a kindof type.
9752  // For example, for common base of kindof(ASub1) and kindof(ASub2), we return
9753  // kindof(A).
9754  bool anyKindOf = LHS->isKindOfType() || RHS->isKindOfType();
9755 
9756  // Follow the left-hand side up the class hierarchy until we either hit a
9757  // root or find the RHS. Record the ancestors in case we don't find it.
9758  llvm::SmallDenseMap<const ObjCInterfaceDecl *, const ObjCObjectType *, 4>
9759  LHSAncestors;
9760  while (true) {
9761  // Record this ancestor. We'll need this if the common type isn't in the
9762  // path from the LHS to the root.
9763  LHSAncestors[LHS->getInterface()->getCanonicalDecl()] = LHS;
9764 
9765  if (declaresSameEntity(LHS->getInterface(), RDecl)) {
9766  // Get the type arguments.
9767  ArrayRef<QualType> LHSTypeArgs = LHS->getTypeArgsAsWritten();
9768  bool anyChanges = false;
9769  if (LHS->isSpecialized() && RHS->isSpecialized()) {
9770  // Both have type arguments, compare them.
9771  if (!sameObjCTypeArgs(*this, LHS->getInterface(),
9772  LHS->getTypeArgs(), RHS->getTypeArgs(),
9773  /*stripKindOf=*/true))
9774  return {};
9775  } else if (LHS->isSpecialized() != RHS->isSpecialized()) {
9776  // If only one has type arguments, the result will not have type
9777  // arguments.
9778  LHSTypeArgs = {};
9779  anyChanges = true;
9780  }
9781 
9782  // Compute the intersection of protocols.
9783  SmallVector<ObjCProtocolDecl *, 8> Protocols;
9784  getIntersectionOfProtocols(*this, LHS->getInterface(), Lptr, Rptr,
9785  Protocols);
9786  if (!Protocols.empty())
9787  anyChanges = true;
9788 
9789  // If anything in the LHS will have changed, build a new result type.
9790  // If we need to return a kindof type but LHS is not a kindof type, we
9791  // build a new result type.
9792  if (anyChanges || LHS->isKindOfType() != anyKindOf) {
9793  QualType Result = getObjCInterfaceType(LHS->getInterface());
9794  Result = getObjCObjectType(Result, LHSTypeArgs, Protocols,
9795  anyKindOf || LHS->isKindOfType());
9796  return getObjCObjectPointerType(Result);
9797  }
9798 
9799  return getObjCObjectPointerType(QualType(LHS, 0));
9800  }
9801 
9802  // Find the superclass.
9803  QualType LHSSuperType = LHS->getSuperClassType();
9804  if (LHSSuperType.isNull())
9805  break;
9806 
9807  LHS = LHSSuperType->castAs<ObjCObjectType>();
9808  }
9809 
9810  // We didn't find anything by following the LHS to its root; now check
9811  // the RHS against the cached set of ancestors.
9812  while (true) {
9813  auto KnownLHS = LHSAncestors.find(RHS->getInterface()->getCanonicalDecl());
9814  if (KnownLHS != LHSAncestors.end()) {
9815  LHS = KnownLHS->second;
9816 
9817  // Get the type arguments.
9818  ArrayRef<QualType> RHSTypeArgs = RHS->getTypeArgsAsWritten();
9819  bool anyChanges = false;
9820  if (LHS->isSpecialized() && RHS->isSpecialized()) {
9821  // Both have type arguments, compare them.
9822  if (!sameObjCTypeArgs(*this, LHS->getInterface(),
9823  LHS->getTypeArgs(), RHS->getTypeArgs(),
9824  /*stripKindOf=*/true))
9825  return {};
9826  } else if (LHS->isSpecialized() != RHS->isSpecialized()) {
9827  // If only one has type arguments, the result will not have type
9828  // arguments.
9829  RHSTypeArgs = {};
9830  anyChanges = true;
9831  }
9832 
9833  // Compute the intersection of protocols.
9834  SmallVector<ObjCProtocolDecl *, 8> Protocols;
9835  getIntersectionOfProtocols(*this, RHS->getInterface(), Lptr, Rptr,
9836  Protocols);
9837  if (!Protocols.empty())
9838  anyChanges = true;
9839 
9840  // If we need to return a kindof type but RHS is not a kindof type, we
9841  // build a new result type.
9842  if (anyChanges || RHS->isKindOfType() != anyKindOf) {
9843  QualType Result = getObjCInterfaceType(RHS->getInterface());
9844  Result = getObjCObjectType(Result, RHSTypeArgs, Protocols,
9845  anyKindOf || RHS->isKindOfType());
9846  return getObjCObjectPointerType(Result);
9847  }
9848 
9849  return getObjCObjectPointerType(QualType(RHS, 0));
9850  }
9851 
9852  // Find the superclass of the RHS.
9853  QualType RHSSuperType = RHS->getSuperClassType();
9854  if (RHSSuperType.isNull())
9855  break;
9856 
9857  RHS = RHSSuperType->castAs<ObjCObjectType>();
9858  }
9859 
9860  return {};
9861 }
9862 
9863 bool ASTContext::canAssignObjCInterfaces(const ObjCObjectType *LHS,
9864  const ObjCObjectType *RHS) {
9865  assert(LHS->getInterface() && "LHS is not an interface type");
9866  assert(RHS->getInterface() && "RHS is not an interface type");
9867 
9868  // Verify that the base decls are compatible: the RHS must be a subclass of
9869  // the LHS.
9870  ObjCInterfaceDecl *LHSInterface = LHS->getInterface();
9871  bool IsSuperClass = LHSInterface->isSuperClassOf(RHS->getInterface());
9872  if (!IsSuperClass)
9873  return false;
9874 
9875  // If the LHS has protocol qualifiers, determine whether all of them are
9876  // satisfied by the RHS (i.e., the RHS has a superset of the protocols in the
9877  // LHS).
9878  if (LHS->getNumProtocols() > 0) {
9879  // OK if conversion of LHS to SuperClass results in narrowing of types
9880  // ; i.e., SuperClass may implement at least one of the protocols
9881  // in LHS's protocol list. Example, SuperObj<P1> = lhs<P1,P2> is ok.
9882  // But not SuperObj<P1,P2,P3> = lhs<P1,P2>.
9883  llvm::SmallPtrSet<ObjCProtocolDecl *, 8> SuperClassInheritedProtocols;
9884  CollectInheritedProtocols(RHS->getInterface(), SuperClassInheritedProtocols);
9885  // Also, if RHS has explicit quelifiers, include them for comparing with LHS's
9886  // qualifiers.
9887  for (auto *RHSPI : RHS->quals())
9888  CollectInheritedProtocols(RHSPI, SuperClassInheritedProtocols);
9889  // If there is no protocols associated with RHS, it is not a match.
9890  if (SuperClassInheritedProtocols.empty())
9891  return false;
9892 
9893  for (const auto *LHSProto : LHS->quals()) {
9894  bool SuperImplementsProtocol = false;
9895  for (auto *SuperClassProto : SuperClassInheritedProtocols)
9896  if (SuperClassProto->lookupProtocolNamed(LHSProto->getIdentifier())) {
9897  SuperImplementsProtocol = true;
9898  break;
9899  }
9900  if (!SuperImplementsProtocol)
9901  return false;
9902  }
9903  }
9904 
9905  // If the LHS is specialized, we may need to check type arguments.
9906  if (LHS->isSpecialized()) {
9907  // Follow the superclass chain until we've matched the LHS class in the
9908  // hierarchy. This substitutes type arguments through.
9909  const ObjCObjectType *RHSSuper = RHS;
9910  while (!declaresSameEntity(RHSSuper->getInterface(), LHSInterface))
9911  RHSSuper = RHSSuper->getSuperClassType()->castAs<ObjCObjectType>();
9912 
9913  // If the RHS is specializd, compare type arguments.
9914  if (RHSSuper->isSpecialized() &&
9915  !sameObjCTypeArgs(*this, LHS->getInterface(),
9916  LHS->getTypeArgs(), RHSSuper->getTypeArgs(),
9917  /*stripKindOf=*/true)) {
9918  return false;
9919  }
9920  }
9921 
9922  return true;
9923 }
9924 
9925 bool ASTContext::areComparableObjCPointerTypes(QualType LHS, QualType RHS) {
9926  // get the "pointed to" types
9927  const auto *LHSOPT = LHS->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
9928  const auto *RHSOPT = RHS->getAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>();
9929 
9930  if (!LHSOPT || !RHSOPT)
9931  return false;
9932 
9933  return canAssignObjCInterfaces(LHSOPT, RHSOPT) ||
9934  canAssignObjCInterfaces(RHSOPT, LHSOPT);
9935 }
9936 
9937 bool ASTContext::canBindObjCObjectType(QualType To, QualType From) {
9938  return canAssignObjCInterfaces(
9939  getObjCObjectPointerType(To)->castAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>(),
9940  getObjCObjectPointerType(From)->castAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>());
9941 }
9942 
9943 /// typesAreCompatible - C99 6.7.3p9: For two qualified types to be compatible,
9944 /// both shall have the identically qualified version of a compatible type.
9945 /// C99 6.2.7p1: Two types have compatible types if their types are the
9946 /// same. See 6.7.[2,3,5] for additional rules.
9947 bool ASTContext::typesAreCompatible(QualType LHS, QualType RHS,
9948  bool CompareUnqualified) {
9949  if (getLangOpts().CPlusPlus)
9950  return hasSameType(LHS, RHS);
9951 
9952  return !mergeTypes(LHS, RHS, false, CompareUnqualified).isNull();
9953 }
9954 
9955 bool ASTContext::propertyTypesAreCompatible(QualType LHS, QualType RHS) {
9956  return typesAreCompatible(LHS, RHS);
9957 }
9958 
9959 bool ASTContext::typesAreBlockPointerCompatible(QualType LHS, QualType RHS) {
9960  return !mergeTypes(LHS, RHS, true).isNull();
9961 }
9962 
9963 /// mergeTransparentUnionType - if T is a transparent union type and a member
9964 /// of T is compatible with SubType, return the merged type, else return
9965 /// QualType()
9966 QualType ASTContext::mergeTransparentUnionType(QualType T, QualType SubType,
9967  bool OfBlockPointer,
9968  bool Unqualified) {
9969  if (const RecordType *UT = T->getAsUnionType()) {
9970  RecordDecl *UD = UT->getDecl();
9971  if (UD->hasAttr<TransparentUnionAttr>()) {
9972  for (const auto *I : UD->fields()) {
9973  QualType ET = I->getType().getUnqualifiedType();
9974  QualType MT = mergeTypes(ET, SubType, OfBlockPointer, Unqualified);
9975  if (!MT.isNull())
9976  return MT;
9977  }
9978  }
9979  }
9980 
9981  return {};
9982 }
9983 
9984 /// mergeFunctionParameterTypes - merge two types which appear as function
9985 /// parameter types
9986 QualType ASTContext::mergeFunctionParameterTypes(QualType lhs, QualType rhs,
9987  bool OfBlockPointer,
9988  bool Unqualified) {
9989  // GNU extension: two types are compatible if they appear as a function
9990  // argument, one of the types is a transparent union type and the other
9991  // type is compatible with a union member
9992  QualType lmerge = mergeTransparentUnionType(lhs, rhs, OfBlockPointer,
9993  Unqualified);
9994  if (!lmerge.isNull())
9995  return lmerge;
9996 
9997  QualType rmerge = mergeTransparentUnionType(rhs, lhs, OfBlockPointer,
9998  Unqualified);
9999  if (!rmerge.isNull())
10000  return rmerge;
10001 
10002  return mergeTypes(lhs, rhs, OfBlockPointer, Unqualified);
10003 }
10004 
10005 QualType ASTContext::mergeFunctionTypes(QualType lhs, QualType rhs,
10006  bool OfBlockPointer, bool Unqualified,
10007  bool AllowCXX) {
10008  const auto *lbase = lhs->castAs<FunctionType>();
10009  const auto *rbase = rhs->castAs<FunctionType>();
10010  const auto *lproto = dyn_cast<FunctionProtoType>(lbase);
10011  const auto *rproto = dyn_cast<FunctionProtoType>(rbase);
10012  bool allLTypes = true;
10013  bool allRTypes = true;
10014 
10015  // Check return type
10016  QualType retType;
10017  if (OfBlockPointer) {
10018  QualType RHS = rbase->getReturnType();
10019  QualType LHS = lbase->getReturnType();
10020  bool UnqualifiedResult = Unqualified;
10021  if (!UnqualifiedResult)
10022  UnqualifiedResult = (!RHS.hasQualifiers() && LHS.hasQualifiers());
10023  retType = mergeTypes(LHS, RHS, true, UnqualifiedResult, true);
10024  }
10025  else
10026  retType = mergeTypes(lbase->getReturnType(), rbase->getReturnType(), false,
10027  Unqualified);
10028  if (retType.isNull())
10029  return {};
10030 
10031  if (Unqualified)
10032  retType = retType.getUnqualifiedType();
10033 
10034  CanQualType LRetType = getCanonicalType(lbase->getReturnType());
10035  CanQualType RRetType = getCanonicalType(rbase->getReturnType());
10036  if (Unqualified) {
10037  LRetType = LRetType.getUnqualifiedType();
10038  RRetType = RRetType.getUnqualifiedType();
10039  }
10040 
10041  if (getCanonicalType(retType) != LRetType)
10042  allLTypes = false;
10043  if (getCanonicalType(retType) != RRetType)
10044  allRTypes = false;
10045 
10046  // FIXME: double check this
10047  // FIXME: should we error if lbase->getRegParmAttr() != 0 &&
10048  // rbase->getRegParmAttr() != 0 &&
10049  // lbase->getRegParmAttr() != rbase->getRegParmAttr()?
10050  FunctionType::ExtInfo lbaseInfo = lbase->getExtInfo();
10051  FunctionType::ExtInfo rbaseInfo = rbase->getExtInfo();
10052 
10053  // Compatible functions must have compatible calling conventions
10054  if (lbaseInfo.getCC() != rbaseInfo.getCC())
10055  return {};
10056 
10057  // Regparm is part of the calling convention.
10058  if (lbaseInfo.getHasRegParm() != rbaseInfo.getHasRegParm())
10059  return {};
10060  if (lbaseInfo.getRegParm() != rbaseInfo.getRegParm())
10061  return {};
10062 
10063  if (lbaseInfo.getProducesResult() != rbaseInfo.getProducesResult())
10064  return {};
10065  if (lbaseInfo.getNoCallerSavedRegs() != rbaseInfo.getNoCallerSavedRegs())
10066  return {};
10067  if (lbaseInfo.getNoCfCheck() != rbaseInfo.getNoCfCheck())
10068  return {};
10069 
10070  // FIXME: some uses, e.g. conditional exprs, really want this to be 'both'.
10071  bool NoReturn = lbaseInfo.getNoReturn() || rbaseInfo.getNoReturn();
10072 
10073  if (lbaseInfo.getNoReturn() != NoReturn)
10074  allLTypes = false;
10075  if (rbaseInfo.getNoReturn() != NoReturn)
10076  allRTypes = false;
10077 
10078  FunctionType::ExtInfo einfo = lbaseInfo.withNoReturn(NoReturn);
10079 
10080  if (lproto && rproto) { // two C99 style function prototypes
10081  assert((AllowCXX ||
10082  (!lproto->hasExceptionSpec() && !rproto->hasExceptionSpec())) &&
10083  "C++ shouldn't be here");
10084  // Compatible functions must have the same number of parameters
10085  if (lproto->getNumParams() != rproto->getNumParams())
10086  return {};
10087 
10088  // Variadic and non-variadic functions aren't compatible
10089  if (lproto->isVariadic() != rproto->isVariadic())
10090  return {};
10091 
10092  if (lproto->getMethodQuals() != rproto->getMethodQuals())
10093  return {};
10094 
10095  SmallVector<FunctionProtoType::ExtParameterInfo, 4> newParamInfos;
10096  bool canUseLeft, canUseRight;
10097  if (!mergeExtParameterInfo(lproto, rproto, canUseLeft, canUseRight,
10098  newParamInfos))
10099  return {};
10100 
10101  if (!canUseLeft)
10102  allLTypes = false;
10103  if (!canUseRight)
10104  allRTypes = false;
10105 
10106  // Check parameter type compatibility
10107  SmallVector<QualType, 10> types;
10108  for (unsigned i = 0, n = lproto->getNumParams(); i < n; i++) {
10109  QualType lParamType = lproto->getParamType(i).getUnqualifiedType();
10110  QualType rParamType = rproto->getParamType(i).getUnqualifiedType();
10111  QualType paramType = mergeFunctionParameterTypes(
10112  lParamType, rParamType, OfBlockPointer, Unqualified);
10113  if (paramType.isNull())
10114  return {};
10115 
10116  if (Unqualified)
10117  paramType = paramType.getUnqualifiedType();
10118 
10119  types.push_back(paramType);
10120  if (Unqualified) {
10121  lParamType = lParamType.getUnqualifiedType();
10122  rParamType = rParamType.getUnqualifiedType();
10123  }
10124 
10125  if (getCanonicalType(paramType) != getCanonicalType(lParamType))
10126  allLTypes = false;
10127  if (getCanonicalType(paramType) != getCanonicalType(rParamType))
10128  allRTypes = false;
10129  }
10130 
10131  if (allLTypes) return lhs;
10132  if (allRTypes) return rhs;
10133 
10134  FunctionProtoType::ExtProtoInfo EPI = lproto->getExtProtoInfo();
10135  EPI.ExtInfo = einfo;
10136  EPI.ExtParameterInfos =
10137  newParamInfos.empty() ? nullptr : newParamInfos.data();
10138  return getFunctionType(retType, types, EPI);
10139  }
10140 
10141  if (lproto) allRTypes = false;
10142  if (rproto) allLTypes = false;
10143 
10144  const FunctionProtoType *proto = lproto ? lproto : rproto;
10145  if (proto) {
10146  assert((AllowCXX || !proto->hasExceptionSpec()) && "C++ shouldn't be here");
10147  if (proto->isVariadic())
10148  return {};
10149  // Check that the types are compatible with the types that
10150  // would result from default argument promotions (C99 6.7.5.3p15).
10151  // The only types actually affected are promotable integer
10152  // types and floats, which would be passed as a different
10153  // type depending on whether the prototype is visible.
10154  for (unsigned i = 0, n = proto->getNumParams(); i < n; ++i) {
10155  QualType paramTy = proto->getParamType(i);
10156 
10157  // Look at the converted type of enum types, since that is the type used
10158  // to pass enum values.
10159  if (const auto *Enum = paramTy->getAs<EnumType>()) {
10160  paramTy = Enum->getDecl()->getIntegerType();
10161  if (paramTy.isNull())
10162  return {};
10163  }
10164 
10165  if (paramTy->isPromotableIntegerType() ||
10166  getCanonicalType(paramTy).getUnqualifiedType() == FloatTy)
10167  return {};
10168  }
10169 
10170  if (allLTypes) return lhs;
10171  if (allRTypes) return rhs;
10172 
10173  FunctionProtoType::ExtProtoInfo EPI = proto->getExtProtoInfo();
10174  EPI.ExtInfo = einfo;
10175  return getFunctionType(retType, proto->getParamTypes(), EPI);
10176  }
10177 
10178  if (allLTypes) return lhs;
10179  if (allRTypes) return rhs;
10180  return getFunctionNoProtoType(retType, einfo);
10181 }
10182 
10183 /// Given that we have an enum type and a non-enum type, try to merge them.
10184 static QualType mergeEnumWithInteger(ASTContext &Context, const EnumType *ET,
10185  QualType other, bool isBlockReturnType) {
10186  // C99 6.7.2.2p4: Each enumerated type shall be compatible with char,
10187  // a signed integer type, or an unsigned integer type.
10188  // Compatibility is based on the underlying type, not the promotion
10189  // type.
10190  QualType underlyingType = ET->getDecl()->getIntegerType();
10191  if (underlyingType.isNull())
10192  return {};
10193  if (Context.hasSameType(underlyingType, other))
10194  return other;
10195 
10196  // In block return types, we're more permissive and accept any
10197  // integral type of the same size.
10198  if (isBlockReturnType && other->isIntegerType() &&
10199  Context.getTypeSize(underlyingType) == Context.getTypeSize(other))
10200  return other;
10201 
10202  return {};
10203 }
10204 
10205 QualType ASTContext::mergeTypes(QualType LHS, QualType RHS,
10206  bool OfBlockPointer,
10207  bool Unqualified, bool BlockReturnType) {
10208  // For C++ we will not reach this code with reference types (see below),
10209  // for OpenMP variant call overloading we might.
10210  //
10211  // C++ [expr]: If an expression initially has the type "reference to T", the
10212  // type is adjusted to "T" prior to any further analysis, the expression
10213  // designates the object or function denoted by the reference, and the
10214  // expression is an lvalue unless the reference is an rvalue reference and
10215  // the expression is a function call (possibly inside parentheses).
10216  auto *LHSRefTy = LHS->getAs<ReferenceType>();
10217  auto *RHSRefTy = RHS->getAs<ReferenceType>();
10218  if (LangOpts.OpenMP && LHSRefTy && RHSRefTy &&
10219  LHS->getTypeClass() == RHS->getTypeClass())
10220  return mergeTypes(LHSRefTy->getPointeeType(), RHSRefTy->getPointeeType(),
10221  OfBlockPointer, Unqualified, BlockReturnType);
10222  if (LHSRefTy || RHSRefTy)
10223  return {};
10224 
10225  if (Unqualified) {
10226  LHS = LHS.getUnqualifiedType();
10227  RHS = RHS.getUnqualifiedType();
10228  }
10229 
10230  QualType LHSCan = getCanonicalType(LHS),
10231  RHSCan = getCanonicalType(RHS);
10232 
10233  // If two types are identical, they are compatible.
10234  if (LHSCan == RHSCan)
10235  return LHS;
10236 
10237  // If the qualifiers are different, the types aren't compatible... mostly.
10238  Qualifiers LQuals = LHSCan.getLocalQualifiers();
10239  Qualifiers RQuals = RHSCan.getLocalQualifiers();
10240  if (LQuals != RQuals) {
10241  // If any of these qualifiers are different, we have a type
10242  // mismatch.
10243  if (LQuals.getCVRQualifiers() != RQuals.getCVRQualifiers() ||
10244  LQuals.getAddressSpace() != RQuals.getAddressSpace() ||
10245  LQuals.getObjCLifetime() != RQuals.getObjCLifetime() ||
10246  LQuals.hasUnaligned() != RQuals.hasUnaligned())
10247  return {};
10248 
10249  // Exactly one GC qualifier difference is allowed: __strong is
10250  // okay if the other type has no GC qualifier but is an Objective
10251  // C object pointer (i.e. implicitly strong by default). We fix
10252  // this by pretending that the unqualified type was actually
10253  // qualified __strong.
10254  Qualifiers::GC GC_L = LQuals.getObjCGCAttr();
10255  Qualifiers::GC GC_R = RQuals.getObjCGCAttr();
10256  assert((GC_L != GC_R) && "unequal qualifier sets had only equal elements");
10257 
10258  if (GC_L == Qualifiers::Weak || GC_R == Qualifiers::Weak)
10259  return {};
10260 
10261  if (GC_L == Qualifiers::Strong && RHSCan->isObjCObjectPointerType()) {
10262  return mergeTypes(LHS, getObjCGCQualType(RHS, Qualifiers::Strong));
10263  }
10264  if (GC_R == Qualifiers::Strong && LHSCan->isObjCObjectPointerType()) {
10265  return mergeTypes(getObjCGCQualType(LHS, Qualifiers::Strong), RHS);
10266  }
10267  return {};
10268  }
10269 
10270  // Okay, qualifiers are equal.
10271 
10272  Type::TypeClass LHSClass = LHSCan->getTypeClass();
10273  Type::TypeClass RHSClass = RHSCan->getTypeClass();
10274 
10275  // We want to consider the two function types to be the same for these
10276  // comparisons, just force one to the other.
10277  if (LHSClass == Type::FunctionProto) LHSClass = Type::FunctionNoProto;
10278  if (RHSClass == Type::FunctionProto) RHSClass = Type::FunctionNoProto;
10279 
10280  // Same as above for arrays
10281  if (LHSClass == Type::VariableArray || LHSClass == Type::IncompleteArray)
10282  LHSClass = Type::ConstantArray;
10283  if (RHSClass == Type::VariableArray || RHSClass == Type::IncompleteArray)
10284  RHSClass = Type::ConstantArray;
10285 
10286  // ObjCInterfaces are just specialized ObjCObjects.
10287  if (LHSClass == Type::ObjCInterface) LHSClass = Type::ObjCObject;
10288  if (RHSClass == Type::ObjCInterface) RHSClass = Type::ObjCObject;
10289 
10290  // Canonicalize ExtVector -> Vector.
10291  if (LHSClass == Type::ExtVector) LHSClass = Type::Vector;
10292  if (RHSClass == Type::ExtVector) RHSClass = Type::Vector;
10293 
10294  // If the canonical type classes don't match.
10295  if (LHSClass != RHSClass) {
10296  // Note that we only have special rules for turning block enum
10297  // returns into block int returns, not vice-versa.
10298  if (const auto *ETy = LHS->getAs<EnumType>()) {
10299  return mergeEnumWithInteger(*this, ETy, RHS, false);
10300  }
10301  if (const EnumType* ETy = RHS->getAs<EnumType>()) {
10302  return mergeEnumWithInteger(*this, ETy, LHS, BlockReturnType);
10303  }
10304  // allow block pointer type to match an 'id' type.
10305  if (OfBlockPointer && !BlockReturnType) {
10306  if (LHS->isObjCIdType() && RHS->isBlockPointerType())
10307  return LHS;
10308  if (RHS->isObjCIdType() && LHS->isBlockPointerType())
10309  return RHS;
10310  }
10311  // Allow __auto_type to match anything; it merges to the type with more
10312  // information.
10313  if (const auto *AT = LHS->getAs<AutoType>()) {
10314  if (AT->isGNUAutoType())
10315  return RHS;
10316  }
10317  if (const auto *AT = RHS->getAs<AutoType>()) {
10318  if (AT->isGNUAutoType())
10319  return LHS;
10320  }
10321  return {};
10322  }
10323 
10324  // The canonical type classes match.
10325  switch (LHSClass) {
10326 #define TYPE(Class, Base)
10327 #define ABSTRACT_TYPE(Class, Base)
10328 #define NON_CANONICAL_UNLESS_DEPENDENT_TYPE(Class, Base) case Type::Class:
10329 #define NON_CANONICAL_TYPE(Class, Base) case Type::Class:
10330 #define DEPENDENT_TYPE(Class, Base) case Type::Class:
10331 #include "clang/AST/TypeNodes.inc"
10332  llvm_unreachable("Non-canonical and dependent types shouldn't get here");
10333 
10334  case Type::Auto:
10335  case Type::DeducedTemplateSpecialization:
10336  case Type::LValueReference:
10337  case Type::RValueReference:
10338  case Type::MemberPointer:
10339  llvm_unreachable("C++ should never be in mergeTypes");
10340 
10341  case Type::ObjCInterface:
10342  case Type::IncompleteArray:
10343  case Type::VariableArray:
10344  case Type::FunctionProto:
10345  case Type::ExtVector:
10346  llvm_unreachable("Types are eliminated above");
10347 
10348  case Type::Pointer:
10349  {
10350  // Merge two pointer types, while trying to preserve typedef info
10351  QualType LHSPointee = LHS->castAs<PointerType>()->getPointeeType();
10352  QualType RHSPointee = RHS->castAs<PointerType>()->getPointeeType();
10353  if (Unqualified) {
10354  LHSPointee = LHSPointee.getUnqualifiedType();
10355  RHSPointee = RHSPointee.getUnqualifiedType();
10356  }
10357  QualType ResultType = mergeTypes(LHSPointee, RHSPointee, false,
10358  Unqualified);
10359  if (ResultType.isNull())
10360  return {};
10361  if (getCanonicalType(LHSPointee) == getCanonicalType(ResultType))
10362  return LHS;
10363  if (getCanonicalType(RHSPointee) == getCanonicalType(ResultType))
10364  return RHS;
10365  return getPointerType(ResultType);
10366  }
10367  case Type::BlockPointer:
10368  {
10369  // Merge two block pointer types, while trying to preserve typedef info
10370  QualType LHSPointee = LHS->castAs<BlockPointerType>()->getPointeeType();
10371  QualType RHSPointee = RHS->castAs<BlockPointerType>()->getPointeeType();
10372  if (Unqualified) {
10373  LHSPointee = LHSPointee.getUnqualifiedType();
10374  RHSPointee = RHSPointee.getUnqualifiedType();
10375  }
10376  if (getLangOpts().OpenCL) {
10377  Qualifiers LHSPteeQual = LHSPointee.getQualifiers();
10378  Qualifiers RHSPteeQual = RHSPointee.getQualifiers();
10379  // Blocks can't be an expression in a ternary operator (OpenCL v2.0
10380  // 6.12.5) thus the following check is asymmetric.
10381  if (!LHSPteeQual.isAddressSpaceSupersetOf(RHSPteeQual))
10382  return {};
10383  LHSPteeQual.removeAddressSpace();
10384  RHSPteeQual.removeAddressSpace();
10385  LHSPointee =
10386  QualType(LHSPointee.getTypePtr(), LHSPteeQual.getAsOpaqueValue());
10387  RHSPointee =
10388  QualType(RHSPointee.getTypePtr(), RHSPteeQual.getAsOpaqueValue());
10389  }
10390  QualType ResultType = mergeTypes(LHSPointee, RHSPointee, OfBlockPointer,
10391  Unqualified);
10392  if (ResultType.isNull())
10393  return {};
10394  if (getCanonicalType(LHSPointee) == getCanonicalType(ResultType))
10395  return LHS;
10396  if (getCanonicalType(RHSPointee) == getCanonicalType(ResultType))
10397  return RHS;
10398  return getBlockPointerType(ResultType);
10399  }
10400  case Type::Atomic:
10401  {
10402  // Merge two pointer types, while trying to preserve typedef info
10403  QualType LHSValue = LHS->castAs<AtomicType>()->getValueType();
10404  QualType RHSValue = RHS->castAs<AtomicType>()->getValueType();
10405  if (Unqualified) {
10406  LHSValue = LHSValue.getUnqualifiedType();
10407  RHSValue = RHSValue.getUnqualifiedType();
10408  }
10409  QualType ResultType = mergeTypes(LHSValue, RHSValue, false,
10410  Unqualified);
10411  if (ResultType.isNull())
10412  return {};
10413  if (getCanonicalType(LHSValue) == getCanonicalType(ResultType))
10414  return LHS;
10415  if (getCanonicalType(RHSValue) == getCanonicalType(ResultType))
10416  return RHS;
10417  return getAtomicType(ResultType);
10418  }
10419  case Type::ConstantArray:
10420  {
10421  const ConstantArrayType* LCAT = getAsConstantArrayType(LHS);
10422  const ConstantArrayType* RCAT = getAsConstantArrayType(RHS);
10423  if (LCAT && RCAT && RCAT->getSize() != LCAT->getSize())
10424  return {};
10425 
10426  QualType LHSElem = getAsArrayType(LHS)->getElementType();
10427  QualType RHSElem = getAsArrayType(RHS)->getElementType();
10428  if (Unqualified) {
10429  LHSElem = LHSElem.getUnqualifiedType();
10430  RHSElem = RHSElem.getUnqualifiedType();
10431  }
10432 
10433  QualType ResultType = mergeTypes(LHSElem, RHSElem, false, Unqualified);
10434  if (ResultType.isNull())
10435  return {};
10436 
10437  const VariableArrayType* LVAT = getAsVariableArrayType(LHS);
10438  const VariableArrayType* RVAT = getAsVariableArrayType(RHS);
10439 
10440  // If either side is a variable array, and both are complete, check whether
10441  // the current dimension is definite.
10442  if (LVAT || RVAT) {
10443  auto SizeFetch = [this](const VariableArrayType* VAT,
10444  const ConstantArrayType* CAT)
10445  -> std::pair<bool,llvm::APInt> {
10446  if (VAT) {
10447  Optional<llvm::APSInt> TheInt;
10448  Expr *E = VAT->getSizeExpr();
10449  if (E && (TheInt = E->getIntegerConstantExpr(*this)))
10450  return std::make_pair(true, *TheInt);
10451  return std::make_pair(false, llvm::APSInt());
10452  }
10453  if (CAT)
10454  return std::make_pair(true, CAT->getSize());
10455  return std::make_pair(false, llvm::APInt());
10456  };
10457 
10458  bool HaveLSize, HaveRSize;
10459  llvm::APInt LSize, RSize;
10460  std::tie(HaveLSize, LSize) = SizeFetch(LVAT, LCAT);
10461  std::tie(HaveRSize, RSize) = SizeFetch(RVAT, RCAT);
10462  if (HaveLSize && HaveRSize && !llvm::APInt::isSameValue(LSize, RSize))
10463  return {}; // Definite, but unequal, array dimension
10464  }
10465 
10466  if (LCAT && getCanonicalType(LHSElem) == getCanonicalType(ResultType))
10467  return LHS;
10468  if (RCAT && getCanonicalType(RHSElem) == getCanonicalType(ResultType))
10469  return RHS;
10470  if (LCAT)
10471  return getConstantArrayType(ResultType, LCAT->getSize(),
10472  LCAT->getSizeExpr(),
10473  ArrayType::ArraySizeModifier(), 0);
10474  if (RCAT)
10475  return getConstantArrayType(ResultType, RCAT->getSize(),
10476  RCAT->getSizeExpr(),
10477  ArrayType::ArraySizeModifier(), 0);
10478  if (LVAT && getCanonicalType(LHSElem) == getCanonicalType(ResultType))
10479  return LHS;
10480  if (RVAT && getCanonicalType(RHSElem) == getCanonicalType(ResultType))
10481  return RHS;
10482  if (LVAT) {
10483  // FIXME: This isn't correct! But tricky to implement because
10484  // the array's size has to be the size of LHS, but the type
10485  // has to be different.
10486  return LHS;
10487  }
10488  if (RVAT) {
10489  // FIXME: This isn't correct! But tricky to implement because
10490  // the array's size has to be the size of RHS, but the type
10491  // has to be different.
10492  return RHS;
10493  }
10494  if (getCanonicalType(LHSElem) == getCanonicalType(ResultType)) return LHS;
10495  if (getCanonicalType(RHSElem) == getCanonicalType(ResultType)) return RHS;
10496  return getIncompleteArrayType(ResultType,
10497  ArrayType::ArraySizeModifier(), 0);
10498  }
10499  case Type::FunctionNoProto:
10500  return mergeFunctionTypes(LHS, RHS, OfBlockPointer, Unqualified);
10501  case Type::Record:
10502  case Type::Enum:
10503  return {};
10504  case Type::Builtin:
10505  // Only exactly equal builtin types are compatible, which is tested above.
10506  return {};
10507  case Type::Complex:
10508  // Distinct complex types are incompatible.
10509  return {};
10510  case Type::Vector:
10511  // FIXME: The merged type should be an ExtVector!
10512  if (areCompatVectorTypes(LHSCan->castAs<VectorType>(),
10513  RHSCan->castAs<VectorType>()))
10514  return LHS;
10515  return {};
10516  case Type::ConstantMatrix:
10517  if (areCompatMatrixTypes(LHSCan->castAs<ConstantMatrixType>(),
10518  RHSCan->castAs<ConstantMatrixType>()))
10519  return LHS;
10520  return {};
10521  case Type::ObjCObject: {
10522  // Check if the types are assignment compatible.
10523  // FIXME: This should be type compatibility, e.g. whether
10524  // "LHS x; RHS x;" at global scope is legal.
10525  if (canAssignObjCInterfaces(LHS->castAs<ObjCObjectType>(),
10526  RHS->castAs<ObjCObjectType>()))
10527  return LHS;
10528  return {};
10529  }
10530  case Type::ObjCObjectPointer:
10531  if (OfBlockPointer) {
10532  if (canAssignObjCInterfacesInBlockPointer(
10533  LHS->castAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>(),
10534  RHS->castAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>(), BlockReturnType))
10535  return LHS;
10536  return {};
10537  }
10538  if (canAssignObjCInterfaces(LHS->castAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>(),
10539  RHS->castAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>()))
10540  return LHS;
10541  return {};
10542  case Type::Pipe:
10543  assert(LHS != RHS &&
10544  "Equivalent pipe types should have already been handled!");
10545  return {};
10546  case Type::BitInt: {
10547  // Merge two bit-precise int types, while trying to preserve typedef info.
10548  bool LHSUnsigned = LHS->castAs<BitIntType>()->isUnsigned();
10549  bool RHSUnsigned = RHS->castAs<BitIntType>()->isUnsigned();
10550  unsigned LHSBits = LHS->castAs<BitIntType>()->getNumBits();
10551  unsigned RHSBits = RHS->castAs<BitIntType>()->getNumBits();
10552 
10553  // Like unsigned/int, shouldn't have a type if they don't match.
10554  if (LHSUnsigned != RHSUnsigned)
10555  return {};
10556 
10557  if (LHSBits != RHSBits)
10558  return {};
10559  return LHS;
10560  }
10561  }
10562 
10563  llvm_unreachable("Invalid Type::Class!");
10564 }
10565 
10566 bool ASTContext::mergeExtParameterInfo(
10567  const FunctionProtoType *FirstFnType, const FunctionProtoType *SecondFnType,
10568  bool &CanUseFirst, bool &CanUseSecond,
10569  SmallVectorImpl<FunctionProtoType::ExtParameterInfo> &NewParamInfos) {
10570  assert(NewParamInfos.empty() && "param info list not empty");
10571  CanUseFirst = CanUseSecond = true;
10572  bool FirstHasInfo = FirstFnType->hasExtParameterInfos();
10573  bool SecondHasInfo = SecondFnType->hasExtParameterInfos();
10574 
10575  // Fast path: if the first type doesn't have ext parameter infos,
10576  // we match if and only if the second type also doesn't have them.
10577  if (!FirstHasInfo && !SecondHasInfo)
10578  return true;
10579 
10580  bool NeedParamInfo = false;
10581  size_t E = FirstHasInfo ? FirstFnType->getExtParameterInfos().size()
10582  : SecondFnType->getExtParameterInfos().size();
10583 
10584  for (size_t I = 0; I < E; ++I) {
10585  FunctionProtoType::ExtParameterInfo FirstParam, SecondParam;
10586  if (FirstHasInfo)
10587  FirstParam = FirstFnType->getExtParameterInfo(I);
10588  if (SecondHasInfo)
10589  SecondParam = SecondFnType->getExtParameterInfo(I);
10590 
10591  // Cannot merge unless everything except the noescape flag matches.
10592  if (FirstParam.withIsNoEscape(false) != SecondParam.withIsNoEscape(false))
10593  return false;
10594 
10595  bool FirstNoEscape = FirstParam.isNoEscape();
10596  bool SecondNoEscape = SecondParam.isNoEscape();
10597  bool IsNoEscape = FirstNoEscape && SecondNoEscape;
10598  NewParamInfos.push_back(FirstParam.withIsNoEscape(IsNoEscape));
10599  if (NewParamInfos.back().getOpaqueValue())
10600  NeedParamInfo = true;
10601  if (FirstNoEscape != IsNoEscape)
10602  CanUseFirst = false;
10603  if (SecondNoEscape != IsNoEscape)
10604  CanUseSecond = false;
10605  }
10606 
10607  if (!NeedParamInfo)
10608  NewParamInfos.clear();
10609 
10610  return true;
10611 }
10612 
10613 void ASTContext::ResetObjCLayout(const ObjCContainerDecl *CD) {
10614  ObjCLayouts[CD] = nullptr;
10615 }
10616 
10617 /// mergeObjCGCQualifiers - This routine merges ObjC's GC attribute of 'LHS' and
10618 /// 'RHS' attributes and returns the merged version; including for function
10619 /// return types.
10620 QualType ASTContext::mergeObjCGCQualifiers(QualType LHS, QualType RHS) {
10621  QualType LHSCan = getCanonicalType(LHS),
10622  RHSCan = getCanonicalType(RHS);
10623  // If two types are identical, they are compatible.
10624  if (LHSCan == RHSCan)
10625  return LHS;
10626  if (RHSCan->isFunctionType()) {
10627  if (!LHSCan->isFunctionType())
10628  return {};
10629  QualType OldReturnType =
10630  cast<FunctionType>(RHSCan.getTypePtr())->getReturnType();
10631  QualType NewReturnType =
10632  cast<FunctionType>(LHSCan.getTypePtr())->getReturnType();
10633  QualType ResReturnType =
10634  mergeObjCGCQualifiers(NewReturnType, OldReturnType);
10635  if (ResReturnType.isNull())
10636  return {};
10637  if (ResReturnType == NewReturnType || ResReturnType == OldReturnType) {
10638  // id foo(); ... __strong id foo(); or: __strong id foo(); ... id foo();
10639  // In either case, use OldReturnType to build the new function type.
10640  const auto *F = LHS->castAs<FunctionType>();
10641  if (const auto *FPT = cast<FunctionProtoType>(F)) {
10642  FunctionProtoType::ExtProtoInfo EPI = FPT->getExtProtoInfo();
10643  EPI.ExtInfo = getFunctionExtInfo(LHS);
10644  QualType ResultType =
10645  getFunctionType(OldReturnType, FPT->getParamTypes(), EPI);
10646  return ResultType;
10647  }
10648  }
10649  return {};
10650  }
10651 
10652  // If the qualifiers are different, the types can still be merged.
10653  Qualifiers LQuals = LHSCan.getLocalQualifiers();
10654  Qualifiers RQuals = RHSCan.getLocalQualifiers();
10655  if (LQuals != RQuals) {
10656  // If any of these qualifiers are different, we have a type mismatch.
10657  if (LQuals.getCVRQualifiers() != RQuals.getCVRQualifiers() ||
10658  LQuals.getAddressSpace() != RQuals.getAddressSpace())
10659  return {};
10660 
10661  // Exactly one GC qualifier difference is allowed: __strong is
10662  // okay if the other type has no GC qualifier but is an Objective
10663  // C object pointer (i.e. implicitly strong by default). We fix
10664  // this by pretending that the unqualified type was actually
10665  // qualified __strong.
10666  Qualifiers::GC GC_L = LQuals.getObjCGCAttr();
10667  Qualifiers::GC GC_R = RQuals.getObjCGCAttr();
10668  assert((GC_L != GC_R) && "unequal qualifier sets had only equal elements");
10669 
10670  if (GC_L == Qualifiers::Weak || GC_R == Qualifiers::Weak)
10671  return {};
10672 
10673  if (GC_L == Qualifiers::Strong)
10674  return LHS;
10675  if (GC_R == Qualifiers::Strong)
10676  return RHS;
10677  return {};
10678  }
10679 
10680  if (LHSCan->isObjCObjectPointerType() && RHSCan->isObjCObjectPointerType()) {
10681  QualType LHSBaseQT = LHS->castAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>()->getPointeeType();
10682  QualType RHSBaseQT = RHS->castAs<ObjCObjectPointerType>()->getPointeeType();
10683  QualType ResQT = mergeObjCGCQualifiers(LHSBaseQT, RHSBaseQT);
10684  if (ResQT == LHSBaseQT)
10685  return LHS;
10686  if (ResQT == RHSBaseQT)
10687  return RHS;
10688  }
10689  return {};
10690 }

10693 // Integer Predicates
10694 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//

10696 unsigned ASTContext::getIntWidth(QualType T) const {
10697  if (const auto *ET = T->getAs<EnumType>())
10698  T = ET->getDecl()->getIntegerType();
10699  if (T->isBooleanType())
10700  return 1;
10701  if (const auto *EIT = T->getAs<BitIntType>())
10702  return EIT->getNumBits();
10703  // For builtin types, just use the standard type sizing method
10704  return (unsigned)getTypeSize(T);
10705 }
10706 
10707 QualType ASTContext::getCorrespondingUnsignedType(QualType T) const {
10708  assert((T->hasSignedIntegerRepresentation() || T->isSignedFixedPointType()) &&
10709  "Unexpected type");
10710 
10711  // Turn <4 x signed int> -> <4 x unsigned int>
10712  if (const auto *VTy = T->getAs<VectorType>())
10713  return getVectorType(getCorrespondingUnsignedType(VTy->getElementType()),
10714  VTy->getNumElements(), VTy->getVectorKind());
10715 
10716  // For _BitInt, return an unsigned _BitInt with same width.
10717  if (const auto *EITy = T->getAs<BitIntType>())
10718  return getBitIntType(/*Unsigned=*/true, EITy->getNumBits());
10719 
10720  // For enums, get the underlying integer type of the enum, and let the general
10721  // integer type signchanging code handle it.
10722  if (const auto *ETy = T->getAs<EnumType>())
10723  T = ETy->getDecl()->getIntegerType();
10724 
10725  switch (T->castAs<BuiltinType>()->getKind()) {
10726  case BuiltinType::Char_S:
10727  case BuiltinType::SChar:
10728  return UnsignedCharTy;
10729  case BuiltinType::Short:
10730  return UnsignedShortTy;
10731  case BuiltinType::Int:
10732  return UnsignedIntTy;
10733  case BuiltinType::Long:
10734  return UnsignedLongTy;
10735  case BuiltinType::LongLong:
10736  return UnsignedLongLongTy;
10737  case BuiltinType::Int128:
10738  return UnsignedInt128Ty;
10739  // wchar_t is special. It is either signed or not, but when it's signed,
10740  // there's no matching "unsigned wchar_t". Therefore we return the unsigned
10741  // version of it's underlying type instead.
10742  case BuiltinType::WChar_S:
10743  return getUnsignedWCharType();
10744 
10745  case BuiltinType::ShortAccum:
10746  return UnsignedShortAccumTy;
10747  case BuiltinType::Accum:
10748  return UnsignedAccumTy;
10749  case BuiltinType::LongAccum:
10750  return UnsignedLongAccumTy;
10751  case BuiltinType::SatShortAccum:
10752  return SatUnsignedShortAccumTy;
10753  case BuiltinType::SatAccum:
10754  return SatUnsignedAccumTy;
10755  case BuiltinType::SatLongAccum:
10756  return SatUnsignedLongAccumTy;
10757  case BuiltinType::ShortFract:
10758  return UnsignedShortFractTy;
10759  case BuiltinType::Fract:
10760  return UnsignedFractTy;
10761  case BuiltinType::LongFract:
10762  return UnsignedLongFractTy;
10763  case BuiltinType::SatShortFract:
10764  return SatUnsignedShortFractTy;
10765  case BuiltinType::SatFract:
10766  return SatUnsignedFractTy;
10767  case BuiltinType::SatLongFract:
10768  return SatUnsignedLongFractTy;
10769  default:
10770  llvm_unreachable("Unexpected signed integer or fixed point type");
10771  }
10772 }
10773 
10774 QualType ASTContext::getCorrespondingSignedType(QualType T) const {
10775  assert((T->hasUnsignedIntegerRepresentation() ||
10776  T->isUnsignedFixedPointType()) &&
10777  "Unexpected type");
10778 
10779  // Turn <4 x unsigned int> -> <4 x signed int>
10780  if (const auto *VTy = T->getAs<VectorType>())
10781  return getVectorType(getCorrespondingSignedType(VTy->getElementType()),
10782  VTy->getNumElements(), VTy->getVectorKind());
10783 
10784  // For _BitInt, return a signed _BitInt with same width.
10785  if (const auto *EITy = T->getAs<BitIntType>())
10786  return getBitIntType(/*Unsigned=*/false, EITy->getNumBits());
10787 
10788  // For enums, get the underlying integer type of the enum, and let the general
10789  // integer type signchanging code handle it.
10790  if (const auto *ETy = T->getAs<EnumType>())
10791  T = ETy->getDecl()->getIntegerType();
10792 
10793  switch (T->castAs<BuiltinType>()->getKind()) {
10794  case BuiltinType::Char_U:
10795  case BuiltinType::UChar:
10796  return SignedCharTy;
10797  case BuiltinType::UShort:
10798  return ShortTy;
10799  case BuiltinType::UInt:
10800  return IntTy;
10801  case BuiltinType::ULong:
10802  return LongTy;
10803  case BuiltinType::ULongLong:
10804  return LongLongTy;
10805  case BuiltinType::UInt128:
10806  return Int128Ty;
10807  // wchar_t is special. It is either unsigned or not, but when it's unsigned,
10808  // there's no matching "signed wchar_t". Therefore we return the signed
10809  // version of it's underlying type instead.
10810  case BuiltinType::WChar_U:
10811  return getSignedWCharType();
10812 
10813  case BuiltinType::UShortAccum:
10814  return ShortAccumTy;
10815  case BuiltinType::UAccum:
10816  return AccumTy;
10817  case BuiltinType::ULongAccum:
10818  return LongAccumTy;
10819  case BuiltinType::SatUShortAccum:
10820  return SatShortAccumTy;
10821  case BuiltinType::SatUAccum:
10822  return SatAccumTy;
10823  case BuiltinType::SatULongAccum:
10824  return SatLongAccumTy;
10825  case BuiltinType::UShortFract:
10826  return ShortFractTy;
10827  case BuiltinType::UFract:
10828  return FractTy;
10829  case BuiltinType::ULongFract:
10830  return LongFractTy;
10831  case BuiltinType::SatUShortFract:
10832  return SatShortFractTy;
10833  case BuiltinType::SatUFract:
10834  return SatFractTy;
10835  case BuiltinType::SatULongFract:
10836  return SatLongFractTy;
10837  default:
10838  llvm_unreachable("Unexpected unsigned integer or fixed point type");
10839  }
10840 }

10847 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//
10848 // Builtin Type Computation
